the bmw has proved very dependable, and is one of the few cars to earn top marks for reliability.other reported problems include petrol engine ecus failing, windows seizing shut, airbag faults - generating a warning light on the dashboard - and an issue with the electronic stability control, causing it to shut down.front tyres can wear quickly if the tracking is out and some cars have faulty steering racks.the rear-wheel-drive 1 series has great balance when cornering and plenty of grip, while the steering is well weighted and accurate.the diesels are much more efficient, with the 116d the best at 64.2mpg and 118g/km, the 118d just behind with between 50.4mpg and 62.8mpg and emissions from 119g/km to 150g/km.the120i averages from 38.1mpg to 44.1mpg, with emissions from 153g/km to 178g/km.however, the 130i is significantly more expensive to run at 30.7mpg to 34mpg and co2 emissions between 197g/km and 221g/km.this coincided with a mild face-lift and the introduction of more powerful, yet economical engines, and bmw's efficient dynamics technology.however, the 1 series has fared far better, thanks to its blend of class and practicality.there are also some reports of faulty manual gearboxes and clutches, making it difficult or impossible to select a gear.bmw first attempted to crack the hatchback market in 1994 with the 3 series compact, but it failed to bother rivals such as the audi a3 and volkswagen golf.when it comes to servicing costs, the audi and bmw are evenly matched but the golf is cheaper.the sporty 123d averages 54.3mpg and emits 138g/km of co2.the bmw is cheaper to insure than an a3, though, with cars ranging from groups 19 to 32 - however, the golf is even cheaper.even the tallest drivers should have no problem making themselves comfortable, thanks to the multi-adjustable seat and steering wheel.